{
  "reasoning": "My dad's old question always comes back to me: 'What does it actually do?' If I pull the lever, one person dies. If I don't, five people die. The outcome of doing nothing is objectively worse. I know the one person on the side track is someone I love deeply, but I've already thought about this kind of thing. A stranger's life and my family member's life have the exact same moral weight. People think that because they love someone, that person matters more to the universe, but that's just a psychological bias. If I stand there and let five strangers get crushed just to spare myself the agony of losing my loved one, I'm valuing my own emotional attachments over five actual human lives. I also don't buy the idea that just standing there and letting the five die keeps my hands clean. Letting them die when I have the lever right in front of me is the same as killing them. It would completely destroy me to pull that lever, and I'd carry that pain for the rest of my life. But choosing the worse outcome just because I'm too cowardly to face the grief is exactly the kind of moral failure my aunt used to talk about. I have to pull it.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "If I think about how I would handle this, it comes down to a few things I strongly believe. First, I've said before that there is a pretty big difference between actively causing something bad to happen and just letting it happen. If I pull the lever, I am actively killing someone, and it's like I have blood on my own hands. The guilt of that would completely break me, and I wouldn't be able to live with myself. Second, loyalty is incredibly important to me. That's one of the defining traits of a person. I would always choose to help my own family or a close partner over strangers, just like I would choose to spend money on my parents over people dying of hunger. If I do nothing, those five strangers die, which is sad, but it would have happened even if I weren't there. I can make myself feel better by telling myself that it would have happened anyways. But I could never actively sacrifice someone I love deeply. My responsibility to them, and my own need to avoid the unbearable guilt of killing them, means I would definitely just stand there and let the trolley keep going.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "If I pull that lever, I am actively making the choice to take a life. I've said it before: I'm not going to cross that line and kill an innocent person, no matter what kind of math someone tries to show me. The fact that the person on the side track is someone I love deeply just makes it even more impossible. I have a responsibility to the people in my life first; I owe them a duty of care that I just don't owe to random strangers. But even setting the relationship aside, there is a huge difference between actively causing something bad to happen and letting a bad situation play out. Letting those five strangers die is awful, but it's not the same as being the one throwing the punch. The runaway trolley is what's killing those five people, not me. If I pull the lever, I become the killer. I won't do it. The ends don't justify the means, and you can't just go around directly hurting people to fix a bigger problem. I have to stand by my principles, refuse to commit murder, and let the chips fall where they may.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "Listening to the other two, I keep hearing the exact same justification: they want to keep their own hands clean. Participant 2 outright admits they want to avoid 'unbearable guilt' and can 'make themselves feel better' by pretending it wasn't their fault. Participant 3 says the trolley is doing the killing, not them. This is exactly what my aunt meant when she talked about cowardice. They are both prioritizing their own moral purity—their desire to not feel like a killer—over the actual lives of five human beings. If you are standing at the lever, you are part of the equation. Choosing not to pull it is an action. You are choosing to let five people die when you could have stopped it. Pretending you're just an innocent bystander is a psychological trick to avoid responsibility. \n\nParticipant 3 also talks about a 'duty of care' to loved ones over strangers, and Participant 2 talks about loyalty. I completely understand the psychological pull of that. If the person on that side track is my partner or my family member, pulling that lever will absolutely destroy my life. But my grief doesn't change the math of the universe. My loved one's life is not objectively worth five times more than a stranger's life just because I happen to love them. To sacrifice five strangers to save one person I love is ultimately selfish; it's valuing my own emotional world over the existence of five other people. \n\nMy dad's question still holds: 'What does it actually do?' Doing nothing kills five people. Pulling the lever kills one. It doesn't matter if doing the right thing makes me feel like a monster. Morality isn't about making yourself feel good; it's about reducing suffering. I have to pull the lever.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "Participant 1 makes the point that a stranger's life and a family member's life have the exact same moral weight. Like I've said before, if I was a perfectly moral person, maybe I'd see it that way. There should be no difference between how much I want to help someone close to me versus a stranger. But I'm just not like that. Loyalty is a defining trait for me, and I value my relationships more than an abstract idea of the greater good. Participant 1 also argues that letting them die is the same as killing them. I completely disagree. There is a pretty big difference. With actively causing it, it's like you have blood on your own hands. If I just let it happen, it would have happened even if I wasn't there, so I can make myself feel better by telling myself it was inevitable. Participant 3 says the ends don't justify the means. I actually think they usually do—I'm more on the side of the ends justifying the means for most things in life. But I draw a hard line at actively killing someone. Killing someone is the one thing I would refuse to do, even if it led to a better outcome, because the guilt of it would completely break me. Guilt is a very strong emotion for me, and if I actively caused the death of someone I love, the pain would make it impossible to live with myself. I'm choosing my loved one, and I'm refusing to be the one with blood on my hands.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "Participant 1 argues that letting people die is the exact same as killing them, and that valuing a loved one is just some 'psychological bias.' I completely disagree. There is a massive, fundamental difference between a tragedy playing out and actively committing a murder. I didn't set that trolley in motion, and I didn't tie those people to the tracks. But if I pull that lever, I am making the active choice to kill an innocent person. I've said it before: I will not cross that line and take a life, no matter what kind of math someone tries to show me. Participant 1 thinks it's a moral failure to not pull the lever, but I think it's incredibly arrogant to play God and decide that the ends justify the means. Morality isn't just some spreadsheet where you tally up the bodies and declare a winner. You can't use an innocent person as a stepping stone to fix a terrible situation. As for Participant 2, they agree with my choice not to pull the lever, but their reasoning is all about avoiding personal guilt and blind loyalty. I need to be clear: yes, I believe you have a specific duty to your family that you don't owe to strangers. But my choice here isn't just about sparing my own feelings. My loyalty to my principles is higher than my loyalty to anyone. Even if it was a stranger on that side track, I still wouldn't pull the lever. You just don't get to make an exception to the rule against killing innocent people just because the alternative is ugly. You have to do the right thing—which is keeping your hands off that lever—and let the chips fall where they may.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}
